    <br />
    <small>Click the button below to Manage Blogs with <a href="http://knockoutjs.com/">Knockout.js</a>, such as creating/editing/viewing and deleting:</small>
    <p><a href="@Url.Content("~/BlogsKnockout")" class="btn btn-danger"> Manage Blogs KO &raquo;</a></p>
</div>

<div class="container-fluid">
    <div class="row">
        <div class="alert alert-warning alert-dismissible" role="alert">
            <h3><strong>About</strong></h3>
        </div>
        <p>
            <a href="http://knockoutjs.com/">Knockout.js</a> is a open source, standalone, JavaScript library that enables declarative bindings using an view model following
            the <a href="https://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/ee817669.aspx">Observer</a> and <a href="https://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/hh848246.aspx">MVVM</a> pattern.
            It enables the UI to project behavior similiar to auto-updating and/or refreshing without required user interaction, whenever data that has
            been bound is modified. Knockout.js also provides its own templating pattern that helps you bind data quickly using a flattened view model.
        </p>

    </div>

    <br />

    <div class="row">
        <div class="col-md-6">
            <h4>Observer</h4>
            <img src="~/Content/observer.gif" alt="" />
            <img src="~/Content/observer2.gif" alt="" />
        </div>

        <div class="col-md-6">
            <h4>Model View View Model</h4>
            <img src="~/Content/MVVM.png" alt="" />
        </div>
    </div>

    <br /><br />

    <p><h4><strong>MVVM with MVC and Knockout:</strong></h4></p>

    <ul>
        <li>
            Model: same model as in MVC
        </li>
        <li>
            View: same view as in MVC
        </li>
        <li>
            View Model: client-side data and operations for UI
        </li>
    </ul>

    <br /><br />

    <p><h4><strong>Observables: </strong> <small>our viewModel is mainly made of these, which helps when attempting to do exchanges on the client-side</small></h4></p>

    <ul>
        <li>
            Objects that can notify other objects of changes
        </li>
        <li>
            They can be observerd by other objects that are dependent
        </li>
        <li>
            <img src="~/Content/obervables.JPG" alt="" />
        </li>
    </ul>

    <br /><br />

    <p><h4><strong>Underlying Principles:</strong></h4></p>
    <ul>
        <li>
            Clear separation between domain data, view components and data to be displayed
        </li>
        <li>
            Presence of a clearly defined layer of specialized code to manage the relationships between the view components
        </li>
    </ul>

